column7: If A is the sister of B, B is the sister of C, and C is the mother of D, then what relation is D to A?
column16: Yes! I love word problems and data structures. Let's think through this step by step. A is the sister of B B is the sister of C C is the mother of D Calculating... A is the sister of C A is the aunt of D Answer: D is A's niece. Generalized algorithm: 1. Use a directed graph to model the connections where person is a vertex and each relationship is an edge. 2. Add edges based on a set of rules. In this case the rules are: * 'mother'/'sister' edges create an 'aunt' edge * two 'sister' edges create a direct 'sister' edge 3. Repeatedly apply rules until there are no longer any new edges added.

We need to find two terms whose product is (x^2 - y^2). Since this is a difference of two squares, we can factor it as: (x^2 - y^2) = (x - y)(x + y) 3. I get the following when running apt update:
Key is stored in legacy trusted.gpg keyring (/etc/apt/trusted.gpg), see the DEPRECATION section in apt-key(8) for details

Why is this warning shown, and how can it be fixed?
column16: The public key used to sign packages in your APT repository is stored in an outdated format. This format, known as the legacy trusted keyring, is no longer recommended for use and is considered deprecated. To fix this warning, you can update the key to the new format using the apt-key command. 1. Backup your legacy trusted keyring: sudo cp /etc/apt/trusted.gpg /etc/apt/trusted.gpg.bak 2. Remove the legacy trusted keyring: sudo rm /etc/apt/trusted.gpg 3. Import the key into the new format: sudo apt-key add /etc/apt/trusted.gpg.bak 3. Update the package list: sudo apt update

To fix this issue, you will need to move the key from the /etc/apt/trusted.gpg file to the /etc/apt/trusted.gpg.d folder. column7: Is there an important difference between the mRNA shots for COVID and the shots developed with the "viral vector" technology (such as the Johnson & Johnson one)?
column16: Yes, according to Yale Medicine - https://www.yalemedicine.org/news/covid-19-vaccine-comparison - mRNA shots like those from Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna work by sending instructions to host cells in the body for making copies of a spike protein" whereas the Johnson & Johnson vaccine uses a harmless adenovirus "as a shell to carry genetic code on the spike proteins to the cells (similar to a Trojan Horse).
